8 9–210.1.
9 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
10 INDICATED.
11 (2) “COHABITANT” MEANS AN INDIVIDUAL WHO FOR A PERIOD OF AT
12 LEAST 180 DAYS IN THE YEAR BEFORE THE DEATH OF A FALLEN JUDICIAL OFFICER:
13 (I) HAD A RELATIONSHIP OF MUTUAL INTERDEPENDENCE
14 WITH THE FALLEN JUDICIAL OFFICER; AND
15 (II) RESIDED WITH THE FALLEN JUDICIAL OFFICER IN THE
16 DWELLING.
17 (3) “DISABLED JUDICIAL OFFICER” MEANS AN INDIVIDUAL WHO:
18 (I) HAS BEEN FOUND TO BE PERMANENTLY AND TOTALLY
19 DISABLED BY AN ADMINISTRATIVE BODY OR COURT OF COMPETENT JURISDICTION
20 AUTHORIZED TO MAKE SUCH A DETERMINATION; AND
21 (II) BECAME DISABLED:
22 1. AS A RESULT OF OR IN THE COURSE OF EMPLOYMENT
23 AS A JUDICIAL OFFICER; OR
24 2. WHILE IN ACTIVE SERVICE AS A JUDICIAL OFFICER,
25 UNLESS THE DISABILITY WAS THE RESULT OF THE INDIVIDUAL’S OWN WILLFUL
26 MISCONDUCT OR ABUSE OF ALCOHOL OR DRUGS.
27 (4) (I) “DWELLING” MEANS REAL PROPERTY THAT:
28 1. IS THE LEGAL RESIDENCE OF A DISABLED JUDICIAL
29 OFFICER, A SURVIVING SPOUSE, OR A COHABITANT; AND

6 SENATE BILL 328
1 2. IS OCCUPIED BY NOT MORE THAN TWO FAMILIES.
2 (II) “DWELLING” INCLUDES THE LOT OR CURTILAGE AND
3 STRUCTURES NECESSARY TO USE THE REAL PROPERTY AS A RESIDENCE.
4 (5) “FALLEN JUDICIAL OFFICER” MEANS AN INDIVIDUAL WHO DIES:
5 (I) AS A RESULT OF OR IN THE COURSE OF EMPLOYMENT AS A
6 JUDICIAL OFFICER; OR
7 (II) WHILE IN ACTIVE SERVICE AS A JUDICIAL OFFICER, UNLESS
8 THE DEATH WAS THE RESULT OF THE INDIVIDUAL’S OWN WILLFUL MISCONDUCT OR
9 ABUSE OF ALCOHOL OR DRUGS.
10 (6) “SURVIVING SPOUSE” MEANS A SURVIVING SPOUSE, WHO HAS NOT
11 REMARRIED, OF A FALLEN JUDICIAL OFFICER.
12 (B) THE MAYOR AND CITY COUNCIL OF BALTIMORE CITY OR THE
13 GOVERNING BODY OF A COUNTY OR MUNICIPAL CORPORATION MAY GRANT, BY LAW,
14 A PROPERTY TAX CREDIT UNDER THIS SECTION AGAINST THE COUNTY OR
15 MUNICIPAL CORPORATION PROPERTY TAX IMPOSED ON A DWELLING THAT IS
16 OWNED BY A DISABLED JUDICIAL OFFICER, A SURVIVING SPOUSE, OR A
17 COHABITANT:
18 (1) IF THE DWELLING WAS OWNED BY THE DISABLED JUDICIAL
19 OFFICER AT THE TIME THE JUDICIAL OFFICER WAS ADJUDGED TO BE PERMANENTLY
20 AND TOTALLY DISABLED OR BY THE FALLEN JUDICIAL OFFICER AT THE TIME OF THE
21 FALLEN JUDICIAL OFFICER’S DEATH;
22 (2) IF THE DISABLED JUDICIAL OFFICER WAS DOMICILED IN THE
23 STATE AS OF, OR ANY TIME WITHIN THE 5 YEARS BEFORE, THE DATE THE DISABLED
24 JUDICIAL OFFICER WAS ADJUDGED TO BE PERMANENTLY AND TOTALLY DISABLED
25 OR THE FALLEN JUDICIAL OFFICER, THE SURVIVING SPOUSE, OR THE COHABITANT
26 WAS DOMICILED IN THE STATE AS OF, OR ANY TIME WITHIN THE 5 YEARS BEFORE,
27 THE DATE OF THE FALLEN JUDICIAL OFFICER’S DEATH AND THE DWELLING WAS
28 ACQUIRED BY THE DISABLED JUDICIAL OFFICER WITHIN 10 YEARS AFTER THE DATE
29 THE DISABLED JUDICIAL OFFICER WAS ADJUDGED TO BE PERMANENTLY AND
30 TOTALLY DISABLED OR BY THE SURVIVING SPOUSE OR COHABITANT WITHIN 10
31 YEARS AFTER THE FALLEN JUDICIAL OFFICER’S DEATH;
32 (3) IF THE DWELLING WAS OWNED BY THE SURVIVING SPOUSE OR
33 COHABITANT AT THE TIME OF THE FALLEN JUDICIAL OFFICER’S DEATH; OR

SENATE BILL 328 7
1 (4) IF THE DWELLING WAS ACQUIRED AFTER THE DISABLED JUDICIAL
2 OFFICER, THE SURVIVING SPOUSE, OR THE COHABITANT QUALIFIED FOR A CREDIT
3 FOR A FORMER DWELLING UNDER ITEM (1), (2), OR (3) OF THIS SUBSECTION, TO THE
4 EXTENT OF THE PREVIOUS CREDIT.
5 (C) A COUNTY OR MUNICIPAL CORPORATION:
6 (1) SHALL DEFINE, BY LAW, WHO IS A JUDICIAL OFFICER; AND
7 (2) MAY PROVIDE, BY LAW, FOR:
8 (I) THE AMOUNT AND DURATION OF A PROPERTY TAX CREDIT
9 ALLOWED UNDER THIS SECTION;
10 (II) ANY ADDITIONAL LIMITATION TO THE NUMBER OF YEARS
11 THE DWELLING WAS ACQUIRED WITHIN THE DATE OF AN ADJUDICATION OF
12 DISABILITY OR DEATH; AND
13 (III) ANY OTHER PROVISION NECESSARY TO CARRY OUT THE
14 PROVISIONS OF THIS SECTION.
15 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect June
16 1, 2026, and shall be applicable to all taxable years beginning after June 30, 2026.
